            "terminalCommandOutput": {
              "text": "\u001b[36mxt() for p in r.pages))\"\r\n\u001b[0mTechnical Exam - Task\r\nGoal: Build a small end-to-end data pipeline that produces a fine-tuning-ready dataset for a\r\nmedia bias classifier. We care more about your decisions, judgment, and code quality than\r\nabout achieving state-of-the-art results.\r\nTime budget: ~4-6 hours of focused work.If you reach the time limit, stop and document what\r\nyou'd do with more time. That's a valid and valued outcome.\r\nDeliverable: A git repository (or zip) containing your code, the dataset you produced, and a\r\nREADME.md report.\r\nWhat We're Evaluating\r\nYou will be assessed on:\r\nWe are not evaluating final classifier accuracy. We are not running your code against a hidden\r\ntest set. This is about how you think and work.\r\nWe allow/expect you to use AI coding assistants. But: expect to be asked about specific parts of\r\nyour code and the choices behind them. Submissions that look like AI output the candidate\r\ncan't explain will not pass.\r\nThe Task\r\n1. Judgment and scoping: Did you make sensible choices given the time budget? Did you\r\nrecognize and document trade-offs?\r\n2. Code quality: Is the code readable, organized, and something you could hand to a\r\nteammate?\r\n3. Data quality awareness: Do you understand the limitations of what you produced?\r\n4. Communication: Is the report clear, honest, and useful?\r\n5. Technical execution: Does the pipeline run end-to-end and produce sensible output?\r\nIf possible, include your prompts, and if you used an agent, the plan it produced.\r\n1. Choose a bias detection sub-task\r\nPick one specific sub-task of \"media bias detection\":\r\nselected from a published media bias survey\r\nYour sub-task should be measurable in both text and image content\r\nJustify your choice in the report: why this sub-task, why it's tractable in the time budget,\r\nand why it's measurable from your data.\r\n\r\n2. Collect articles:\r\nBuild a small crawler that fetches articles\r\nTarget (100-300 articles)\r\nLibraries can be used\r\n3. Processing:\r\nClean and structure the articles into a format suitable for downstream labeling. Decisions to\r\nmake and document briefly in report.\r\ne.g., (verify content/clean, split in sentences, images)\r\nSchema of your processed data\r\n4. Pre-Label:\r\nFind an off-the-shelf classifier on HuggingFace whose task is related but not identical to\r\nyour chosen sub-task (e.g., a subjectivity classifier as a proxy for opinion-vs-fact framing).\r\nRun it on your data and store predictions in your schema.\r\nIn your report, explain why this model is a reasonable proxy and where you expect it to\r\ndisagree with your target task.\r\n5. LLM + VLM annotation:\r\nAnnotate a sample (50-100 samples) with both an LLM and a VLM. Include the prompts in\r\nthe repository. You can use a small local model.\r\nLLM: produce a label for your chosen task plus a short natural-language explanation.\r\nVLM: for each article's main image, produce a description and an assessment of\r\nwhether the image (and related text) contains bias, plus a short explanation.\r\n6. EDA\r\nDescriptive analysis of your dataset.\r\nAgreement analysis between the proxy classifier labels (step 4) and the LLM\r\nannotations (step 5)\r\n7. Report\r\nWrite a short report on the decisions made (can be README.md)\r\nRequired:\r\nTask chosen and why\r\nPipeline overview (one paragraph or a small diagram)\r\nDecisions made, including:\r\nWhy your chosen proxy classifier is a reasonable fit\r\nShortcuts taken (e.g., for time reasons)\r\nRisks of the approach\r\nAI usage\u001b[?1004h",
